\begin_layout Subsection
Derivation of equation 2.12-2.14
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find the momentum carried by the light in each arm of the interferometer
 then the momentum transferred at each bounce is twice this amount (assuming
 the mirrors don't move; for if they do, the reflected light will be Doppler
 shifted).
 Assume the electric field is polarized out of the page.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename caves81_beam splitter.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Pictorial representation of what happens at the beam-splitter
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:beamsplitter"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let mode 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{+}$
\end_inset

 refer to light incident from the input laser port (incident plane wave
 with angular frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Mode 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{+}$
\end_inset

 is the light incident from the unused input port.
 We will assume there is also a laser at the second (mode 2) port.
 Denote the laser E-field by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{laser,mode1} & = & E_{1}=ae^{i\left(kx-\omega t\right)}\\
E_{laser,mode2} & = & E_{2}=ae^{i\left(ky-\omega t\right)}\\
k & = & \omega/c.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Looking at figure 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{fig:beamsplitter}$
\end_inset

, we easily see that mode 
\begin_inset Formula $1+$
\end_inset

 after traversing the beam-splitter becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{1+} & = & \begin{cases}
E_{1}+E_{1}^{R} & y>x\\
E_{1}^{T}
\end{cases}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

To figure out what 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}^{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}^{T}$
\end_inset

 are, we consider a general 50/50 beam-splitter: it introduces a global
 phase shift of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\Delta}$
\end_inset

 to any light that traverses it and a relative 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\mu}$
\end_inset

 to the reflected light.
 However, we also have to take into account the reflection symmety through
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-y$
\end_inset

 (WHY?).
 The transmitted and reflected E-field are 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 that of the incoming E-field (see section 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{sub:Beamsplitter}$
\end_inset

).
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{1}^{T} & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}e^{i\Delta}E_{1}.\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

